## Vehicle Performance and Passenger Comfort Issues

Mountain driving affects different vehicle types in ways that matter for passenger experience. During equipment deliveries, I've observed how elevation, grades, and weather conditions impact various transportation options differently.

Larger vehicles like shuttle vans and buses struggle more with mountain grades and elevation changes. Their higher profile creates more wind resistance, and their greater weight requires more power for hill climbing. I've followed 15-passenger vans that couldn't maintain highway speeds on the steeper sections between Georgetown and the Eisenhower Tunnel.

All-wheel drive capability matters more for mountain transportation than most people realize. Even during dry summer conditions, mountain roads can have gravel, loose rock, or sudden weather changes that make traction critical. I've seen two-wheel drive vehicles struggle on grades that AWD vehicles handle easily.

Air pressure changes affect both vehicles and passengers during the elevation gain to Breckenridge. Tire pressure increases as elevation decreases atmospheric pressure, sometimes requiring adjustment. More importantly, passengers often experience ear pressure changes and mild altitude effects, particularly those traveling from sea level locations.

