## Seasonal Considerations and Planning

Different seasons create unique challenges for Denver Airport to Breckenridge transportation that affect scheduling, vehicle selection, and passenger preparation.

Winter transportation requires traction-law compliance and emergency preparedness. Colorado's traction law mandates AWD vehicles with adequate tread depth or chain-capable vehicles with chains available. Violations carry significant fines and can result in highway removal during enforcement periods.

Spring conditions present the most unpredictable challenges. Rapid weather changes, afternoon thunderstorms, and avalanche danger create situations that require flexible scheduling and experienced drivers. I've encountered everything from snow squalls to flash flooding during April and May deliveries.

Summer transportation faces different challenges including construction delays, afternoon thunderstorms, and increased traffic from recreational visitors. Mountain roads undergo extensive maintenance during the brief summer construction season, creating temporary delays and route changes.

Fall weather begins affecting mountain transportation earlier than most people expect. Snow can occur at high elevations as early as September, and morning frost creates slippery conditions well before winter officially begins. Early season storms often catch travelers unprepared with inappropriate clothing and expectations.

